│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The reproducer's function name `cost_ashr_with_op_known_invariant_via_scev` is a strong hint. It suggests the issue is related to the cost of an arithmetic shift right (`ashr`) where   │
│ one operand is identified as loop-invariant through Scalar Evolution (SCEV) analysis.                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Looking at the IR, we have `%shr.i = ashr i32 %conv5.i, %p.1`.                                                                                                                           │
│ `%conv5.i` is derived from the function argument `%a`, so it's loop-invariant.                                                                                                           │
│ `%p.1` is a phi node: `phi i32 [ %rem.i, %else ], [ 0, %loop.header ]`.                                                                                                                  │
│ The control flow is such that the `else` branch containing the `urem` by zero is unreachable. The value of `%p.1` will be `0` on the first iteration and `0` or `%0` on subsequent       │
│ iterations. `%0` is `ashr exact i32 %sext.i, 24` where `%sext.i = shl i32 %p.1, 24`. This means `%0` is just `%p.1` if it's in the range of a signed 8-bit integer.                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The key instruction is `%shr.i = ashr i32 %conv5.i, %p.1`. The shift amount `%p.1` is not constant but is derived from values within the loop. However, the value being shifted,         │
│ `%conv5.i`, is loop-invariant.                                                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The legacy cost model has a function `getInstructionCost` which calculates the cost of vectorizing an instruction. For a shift instruction, if one operand is loop-invariant, it might   │
│ be cheaper to vectorize because the invariant operand can be broadcasted instead of gathered.                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The VPlan cost model, which is newer, might not have the same logic for handling this specific case of a shift with a loop-invariant operand. This discrepancy could lead to different   │
│ cost assessments and thus different optimal vectorization factors, triggering the assertion.                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A common pattern for fixing such discrepancies is to align the logic of the two cost models. In this case, it seems the legacy model has more refined logic for this specific scenario.  │
│ I will examine `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getInstructionCost` in `LoopVectorize.cpp` to see how it handles shifts.                                                                     │
